than extracellular calcium concentration","Extracellular calcium concentration is higher than intracellular calcium concentration","Hydroxyapatite within the skeleton contains 1% of the body\u0027s calcium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcium homeostasis is a vital physiological process that maintains stable calcium levels in the body, essential for functions such as muscle contraction, nerve transmission, and bone health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eextracellular calcium concentration is higher than intracellular calcium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E. This gradient is crucial for cellular signalling and function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe adult human body contains approximately 2 kg of calcium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as while the body contains a significant amount of calcium, it is not as high as 2 kg. \u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxyapatite within the skeleton contains 1% of the body\u0027s calcium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the skeleton actually contains about 99% of the body\u0027s calcium. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium is primarily stored in the blood\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as most calcium is stored in bones, not in the blood. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntracellular calcium concentration is higher than extracellular calcium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the opposite is true; extracellular calcium concentration is higher.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium homeostasis is crucial for various physiological processes, including muscle contraction, nerve transmission, and bone health.","The majority of calcium in the human body is stored in bones as hydroxyapatite.","Extracellular calcium concentration is higher than intracellular calcium concentration."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 8; pg. 104","Khurana I, Khurana A, Kow